expcor: Quasi-experimental (i.e., at least 1 IV is manipulated and at least 1 IV is measured)
comments: (reported in paper as Study 2a). They reported an F-test result for their individual predictor test (instead of t). They also used F for all simple slopes analyses. I therefore changed the f-test result to t (took the square root) for the relevant boxes in the form. However, I kept their original reporting for the "what did they report" box. Also, they reported the regression as two separate regressions (comparing one experimental condition to control in one regression. then comparing the other experimental condition to control in the other regression). They should have used dummy coded variables in one regression.

first.author: Giguare
citation: Giguare, B., Lalonde, R. N., & Taylor, D. M. (2014). Drinking too much and feeling bad about it? How group identification moderates experiences of guilt and shame following norm transgression. Personality and social psychology bulletin, 40(5), 617-632.
type: Original Research (i.e., any study with data that is NOT a meta-analysis)
expcor: Correlational (i.e., IVs were measured and not manipulated)
comments: The article called it a  "mixed-linear model" and used lme4 but it look like just GLM to me. There were no random effects mentioned. I reported the primary analyses as if they were using GLM. On predictor was within subjects categorical with 2 levels. One predictor was continous. The third predictor was a three level categorical predictor but the article did not say how it was coded and they only report one interaction term for the primary analysis which was a three-way interaction (suggesting they did not dummy code). I reported the number of predictors as if it was a regression analysis (i.e. 3 main effects, 3 two-way interactions, 1 three-way interaction)

first.author: McIntyre
citation: McIntyre, R. B., Paulson, R. M., Lord, C. G., & Lepper, M. R. (2004). Effects of attitude action identification on congruence between attitudes and behavioral intentions toward social groups. Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin, 30(9), 1151-1164.
type: Original Research (i.e., any study with data that is NOT a meta-analysis)
expcor: Correlational (i.e., IVs were measured and not manipulated)
comments:
For the primary analysis, there were two the main effects (entered step 1) and a interaction term (entered step 2). Study reported Beta, Rsq (but not change in Rsq), F for the entire step, and F for the change in R-sq. Step 1 R-sq = .063, Step 2 R-sq = .529 (for calculating change in R-sq, effect size). F test for change in R-sq F(1, 82) = 24.97, p < .001 (to get t for the beta coefficient). Just in case: Step 1 F(2, 84) = 2.82, ns, Step 2 F(3, 83) = 10.74. 

To count the total number of statistical tests. The study reported 3 predictor model (see above) for 10 dvs, i.e. 30 significance tests in a table. However the significance of the betas was not given. The change in r-sq significance for the interaction was given, so the significance of the interaction beta can be determined (10 tests). For the step with the main effects, of the 10 dv's, the main effect step for 8 of them were not significant so neither of the main effects were (16 tests). However, for 2 dv the main effect step was sig, so it is not clear if both main effects are significant or just one (4 test) these 4 are excluded from the count. Additional test in the body of the text were also included.

citation: Gebauer, J. E., Bleidorn, W., Gosling, S. D., Rentfrow, P. J., Lamb, M. E., & Potter, J. (2014). Cross-cultural variations in Big Five relationships with religiosity: A sociocultural motives perspective. Journal of Personality and Social Psychology, 107, 1064–1091.
type: Original Research (i.e., any study with data that is NOT a meta-analysis)
expcor: Correlational (i.e., IVs were measured and not manipulated)
effect.size: the variance explained by a model=14.19%
comments: 1. Study 1a-1d used sub-samples selected from a same dataset by different criteria.  The exact size of this dataset was not reported in the article. 2. They used HLM to analysis the data for the primary research aim, which is to test whether the context factor would influence the results. They only reported the percentage of how much variance would be explained by the context factor, without reporting other information, such as p values. 3. I didn't include the significance test for demographic variables. Because this study did not test the significance of the primary analysis, so I feel this result may not apply for our study. Also, it compared the results for different studies 1a-1d, but it's hard to include any of these tests in our forms.
